%[text] # F02: Calculate Molecular Properties (Descriptors)
%[text] EasyMolKit Basic Tutorial — Layer 1
%[text] 
%[text] For a new drug to be taken orally, it must be absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract (mainly the intestinal epithelium). Can we predict whether a drug will be absorbed based on its chemical structure? Lipinski conducted a statistical analysis of over 2,500 oral drugs and discovered four property thresholds (Ro5) that are common to almost all of them.
%[text] This script calculates molecular descriptors and verifies their significance from a drug discovery perspective.
%[text] **What you will learn in this tutorial**
%[text] - Understand key molecular descriptors (MW, LogP, TPSA, HBD, HBA)
%[text] - Calculate descriptors using `emk.descriptor.calculate`
%[text] - Batch process multiple molecules with `emk.descriptor.batchCalculate`
%[text] - Interpret descriptor values in the context of drug discovery \
%[text] **Requirements**
%[text] - RDKit installed (run `emk.setup.install()` once)
%[text] - F01 completed (or familiar with `emk.mol.fromSmiles`)
%[text] - No additional Toolbox required (works with MATLAB only) \
%[text] Estimated time: 10–15 minutes | How to run: Execute sections one by one with Ctrl+Enter
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
%[text] Initialize the path and Python environment.
%[text] **Always run this section first.**
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:6663ae00]
%[text] Warm up the Python/RDKit process
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight
clear mol_warmup;
logInfo("F02: Setup complete"); %[output:6016bcff]
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Calculate All Descriptors for a Single Molecule
%[text] Using `emk.descriptor.calculate`, you can extract the molecular property values (MW, LogP, TPSA, HBD, HBA, etc.) all at once. The return value is a struct with fields of type double scalar.
%[text] **Note**: If you are not familiar with terms like double or struct, check [Data Types](https://www.mathworks.com/help/matlab/data-types.html?s_tid=CRUX_lftnav) and [Fundamental MATLAB Classes](https://www.mathworks.com/help/matlab/matlab_prog/fundamental-matlab-classes.html). Understanding data types and classes is knowledge applicable across various programming languages and tools, not just MATLAB.
mol = emk.mol.fromSmiles("CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O");   % Aspirin
desc = emk.descriptor.calculate(mol);

logInfo("Aspirin Descriptors:"); %[output:2fc32872]
logInfo("  MolWt            = %.3f g/mol",  desc.MolWt); %[output:3d09f58c]
logInfo("  ExactMolWt       = %.6f g/mol",  desc.ExactMolWt); %[output:77e53ed7]
logInfo("  LogP             = %.3f",         desc.LogP); %[output:3aa396f7]
logInfo("  TPSA             = %.2f A^2",     desc.TPSA); %[output:4574de08]
logInfo("  NumHDonors       = %d",           desc.NumHDonors); %[output:0a9a1acb]
logInfo("  NumHAcceptors    = %d",           desc.NumHAcceptors); %[output:6a0fb813]
logInfo("  NumRotatableBonds= %d",           desc.NumRotatableBonds); %[output:8924acfb]
logInfo("  RingCount        = %d",           desc.RingCount); %[output:4482669c]
logInfo("  FractionCSP3     = %.3f",         desc.FractionCSP3); %[output:32180363]
logInfo("  HeavyAtomCount   = %d",           desc.HeavyAtomCount); %[output:41e7da36]
%[text] 
%[text] **✏️ Try It 1 — Check Ro5 with Another Drug**
%[text] Try calculating the descriptors for Ibuprofen (`"CC(C)CC1=CC=C(C=C1)C(C)C(=O)O"`).
%[text] Does it meet all of Lipinski's Ro5 criteria (MW ≤ 500, LogP ≤ 5, HBD ≤ 5, HBA ≤ 10)?
%[text] Hint: Check `desc.MolWt`, `desc.LogP`, `desc.NumHDonors`, `desc.NumHAcceptors`.
% ... (Write your code here)
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: Select Specific Descriptors Only
%[text] By passing a string array, you can calculate only the necessary descriptors. This can be faster than looping through calculations, as it skips unnecessary descriptors in large datasets.
mol2 = emk.mol.fromSmiles("CN1C=NC2=C1C(=O)N(C(=O)N2C)C");  % Caffeine
subset = emk.descriptor.calculate(mol2, ["MolWt", "LogP", "TPSA"]);
logInfo("Caffeine (Subset): MW=%.2f, LogP=%.2f, TPSA=%.1f", ... %[output:group:6790a36b] %[output:37767c6f]
    subset.MolWt, subset.LogP, subset.TPSA); %[output:group:6790a36b] %[output:37767c6f]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Meaning of Descriptors
%[text] ### TPSA — Indicator of Membrane Permeability
%[text] Cell membranes are lipid (oil) bilayers. Molecules with higher polarity (hydrophilicity) tend to have more difficulty passing through membranes. TPSA is the sum of the areas of the polar parts (O, N, etc.) of the molecular surface.
%[text] - **Oral Absorption Guideline**: TPSA \< 140 Å² (can pass through the intestinal epithelium)
%[text] - **Reaching the Brain**: TPSA \< 90 Å² (the blood-brain barrier is even stricter) \
%[text] Lowering TPSA increases brain permeability, but it may also increase toxicity risks. This is why drug discovery chemists manage TPSA carefully.
%[text] 
%[text] ### Lipinski's Ro5 — The Rule of Five for Oral Drugs
%[text] In 1997, Christopher Lipinski analyzed about 2,500 oral drugs and found that almost all of them meet four simple thresholds (numbers that are multiples of 5 = "Rule of Five"). It is said that molecules violating two or more of the four descriptors have less than a 10% chance of reaching Phase II clinical trials.
%[text] **Note**: However, this does not apply to biologics, prodrugs, or substrates of active transporters. It is heuristic, but widely used in early screening worldwide.
%[text] **Descriptor Quick Reference**
%[text:table]
%[text] | Descriptor | Meaning | Drug-like Guidelines |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | MolWt | Average Molecular Weight \[Da\] | ≤ 500 Da |
%[text] | LogP | Octanol-water partition coefficient (lipophilicity) | ≤ 5 |
%[text] | TPSA | Topological Polar Surface Area \[Å²\] | \< 140 (oral), \< 90 (CNS) |
%[text] | NumHDonors / NumHAcceptors | Number of Hydrogen Bond Donors / Acceptors | ≤ 5 / ≤ 10 |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
molecules = struct( ...
    "name",   {"Ethanol", "Aspirin", "Caffeine", "Ibuprofen"}, ...
    "smiles", {"CCO", "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O", ...
               "CN1C=NC2=C1C(=O)N(C(=O)N2C)C", ...
               "CC(C)CC1=CC=C(C=C1)C(C)C(=O)O"} ...
);
n     = numel(molecules);
Name  = strings(n, 1);
MolWt = zeros(n, 1);
LogP  = zeros(n, 1);
TPSA  = zeros(n, 1);
HBD   = zeros(n, 1);
HBA   = zeros(n, 1);
for i = 1:n
    mol      = emk.mol.fromSmiles(molecules(i).smiles);
    d        = emk.descriptor.calculate(mol, ["MolWt","LogP","TPSA", ...
                                              "NumHDonors","NumHAcceptors"]);
    Name(i)  = molecules(i).name;
    MolWt(i) = d.MolWt;
    LogP(i)  = d.LogP;
    TPSA(i)  = d.TPSA;
    HBD(i)   = d.NumHDonors;
    HBA(i)   = d.NumHAcceptors;
end
loop_tbl = table(Name, MolWt, LogP, TPSA, HBD, HBA);
disp(loop_tbl); %[output:83350dcc]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Batch Processing with batchCalculate
%[text] `emk.descriptor.batchCalculate` processes a cell array of Mol objects in bulk and returns a MATLAB table with 1 row = 1 molecule. To minimize Python IPC overhead, it processes significantly faster than calling `emk.descriptor.calculate` in a loop.
%[text] Load the accompanying everyday\_chemicals dataset (csv) located in the data folder.
data = readtable("data/list/everyday_chemicals.csv", TextType="string");
logInfo("Loaded %d everyday chemicals", height(data)); %[output:050fb996]
%[text] Convert all SMILES to Mol objects.
mols = cellfun(@(s) emk.mol.fromSmiles(s), cellstr(data.SMILES), ...
    "UniformOutput", false);
%[text] Calculate descriptors in bulk.
desc_tbl = emk.descriptor.batchCalculate(mols, ["MolWt","LogP","TPSA"]);
desc_tbl.Name = data.CommonName;   % Add names for display
desc_tbl = movevars(desc_tbl, "Name", "Before", "MolWt");
disp(desc_tbl); %[output:7c8e3aa7]
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Simple Visualization
%[text] Plot the MW and LogP of all compounds in a scatter plot, colored by TPSA. This is a commonly used "property space" plot in drug discovery.
figure("Name", "MW vs LogP", "Position", [100 100 600 450]); %[output:6328a610]
scatter(desc_tbl.LogP, desc_tbl.MolWt, 60, desc_tbl.TPSA, "filled"); %[output:6328a610]
cbar = colorbar(); %[output:6328a610]
cbar.Title.String = "TPSA (A^2)"; %[output:6328a610]
xlabel("LogP  (lipophilicity)"); %[output:6328a610]
ylabel("Molecular Weight  [g/mol]"); %[output:6328a610]
title("Everyday Chemicals -- Property Space"); %[output:6328a610]
%[text] Add boundary lines for Lipinski's Ro5.
hold on; %[output:6328a610]
xline(5,  "r--", "Ro5: LogP=5", "LabelVerticalAlignment", "bottom"); %[output:6328a610]
yline(500,"r--", "Ro5: MW=500", "LabelHorizontalAlignment", "left"); %[output:6328a610]
for i = 1:height(desc_tbl)
    text(desc_tbl.LogP(i), desc_tbl.MolWt(i), "  " + desc_tbl.Name(i), ... %[output:6328a610]
        "FontSize", 7, "Interpreter", "none"); %[output:6328a610]
end
hold off; %[output:6328a610]
ylim([0, 550]);   % Add margin to display the MW=500 line above the top of the plot %[output:6328a610]
%[text] 
%[text] **✏️ Try It 2 — Identify Compounds Outside the Ro5 Zone**
%[text] Try extracting compounds from `desc_tbl` with a logical index for MW \> 500 or LogP \> 5.
%[text] How many everyday chemicals fall outside the Ro5 MW and LogP criteria?
%[text] Hint: You can filter using `desc_tbl(desc_tbl.MolWt > 500 | desc_tbl.LogP > 5, :)`.
% ... (Write your code here)
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Summary
%[text] Here is a list of functions used in this tutorial.
%[text:table]
%[text] | Function | Purpose |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | `emk.descriptor.calculate(mol)` | Calculate all 10 descriptors |
%[text] | `emk.descriptor.calculate(mol, ["MolWt","LogP"])` | Calculate only the selected descriptors |
%[text] | `emk.descriptor.batchCalculate(mols)` | Process N molecules in bulk and return a table |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] **Key thresholds for drug discovery**
%[text] - MolWt ≤ 500, LogP ≤ 5, HBD ≤ 5, HBA ≤ 10 (Lipinski's Ro5)
%[text] - TPSA \< 140 Å² (Indicator of good oral absorption) \
%[text] In the next F03, we will learn about the mechanism and usage of fingerprints that convert molecular structures into "bit vectors".
%%
